<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Male.</emphasis>
Body form (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 27" captionStartId="F27" captionText="Figure 27. Acontiophorus estivalis sp. nov., female A leg 5, dorsal. Male B habitus, dorsal C antennule (setae omitted) D leg 5, dorsal E leg 6. Scale bars: 0.02 mm (A, C-E); 0.1 mm (B)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure27" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720747" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">27B</figureCitation>
) as in female. Body length 890 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in dissected and figured paratype (length range 821-890 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
). Prosome 600 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
long. Cephalothorax slightly wider than long (374 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
407 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
). Urosome five-segmented, Genital somite much wider than long. First two free abdominal somites broadened distally, with pointed posterolateral corners. Caudal ramus 1.44 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide (46 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
32 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
), armed as in female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Antennule (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 27" captionStartId="F27" captionText="Figure 27. Acontiophorus estivalis sp. nov., female A leg 5, dorsal. Male B habitus, dorsal C antennule (setae omitted) D leg 5, dorsal E leg 6. Scale bars: 0.02 mm (A, C-E); 0.1 mm (B)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure27" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720747" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">27C</figureCitation>
) 168 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
long, 11-segmented; setae entangled, difficult to distinguish from one another; aesthetascs five on second segment, two on third, one on each 7th and 10th segment; aesthetasc on 10th segment large. Antenna as in female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Oral siphon, mandible, maxillule, maxilla, maxilliped, and legs 1-4 same as those of female. Leg 5 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 27" captionStartId="F27" captionText="Figure 27. Acontiophorus estivalis sp. nov., female A leg 5, dorsal. Male B habitus, dorsal C antennule (setae omitted) D leg 5, dorsal E leg 6. Scale bars: 0.02 mm (A, C-E); 0.1 mm (B)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure27" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720747" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">27D</figureCitation>
) also shaped as in female; inner distal seta on protopod pinnate; exopodal segment 1.33 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide (32 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
24 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
), armed as in female. Leg 6 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 27" captionStartId="F27" captionText="Figure 27. Acontiophorus estivalis sp. nov., female A leg 5, dorsal. Male B habitus, dorsal C antennule (setae omitted) D leg 5, dorsal E leg 6. Scale bars: 0.02 mm (A, C-E); 0.1 mm (B)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1115.83266.figure27" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720747" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">27E</figureCitation>
) represented by three setae (two larger, weakly pinnate and one smaller naked) on genital operculum.
</paragraph>
